: 0.9996547698974609, "span": {"begin": 771, "end": 782}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005227"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fatty acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996036291122437, "span": {"begin": 803, "end": 813}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014280"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "triglycerides", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993554949760437, "span": {"begin": 820, "end": 833}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3290"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "high-density lipoprotein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9960062503814697, "span": {"begin": 980, "end": 1004}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3290"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HDL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9961710572242737, "span": {"begin": 1006, "end": 1009}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2303", "342184"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "low-density", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9816749095916748, "span": {"begin": 1012, "end": 1023}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3949"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LDL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8022255301475525, "span": {"begin": 1025, "end": 1028}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "very", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.481675386428833, "span": {"begin": 1035, "end": 1039}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7436"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VLDL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8666785955429077, "span": {"begin": 1053, "end": 1057}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992187023162842, "span": {"begin": 1061, "end": 1072}}], "text": "Most cholesterol synthesis in vertebrates occurs within the endoplasmic reticulum of hepatic cells. First, acetyl-CoA is converted to HMG-CoA via HMG-CoA synthase. Next, HMG-CoA is converted to mevalonate via HMG-CoA reductase. Several other steps follow, but conversion of HMG-CoA to mevalonate is the rate-limiting step of cholesterol synthesis (Cerqueira et al. 2016; Risley 2002). Consequently,&nbsp;Statin drugs inhibit HMG-CoA reductase to reduce cholesterol (Pahan 2006).  Cholesterol synthesis may also occur to a limited extent in steroidogenic cells where it&rsquo;s used to produce steroid hormones (Azhar et al., 2007)  Once cholesterol is produced in the liver, it&rsquo;s transported in the plasma. Hydrophobic lipids like cholesterol, cholesteryl ester (a cholesterol molecule bound to a fatty acid), and triglycerides are transported via lipoprotein complexes. There are different groups of lipoproteins which use different proteins and ratios of lipids including high-density lipoprotein (HDL), low-density (LDL), and very low-density (VLDL).  Cholesterol metabolism KEGG Pathway&nbsp; ko04979  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:37:06 +0000 2026"}